Pokémon Go Hunt Brings Health and Happiness
It’s fascinating to see how the world is changing.
Over the past decade, many have complained about why teenagers and children no longer go out to play, but rather stay inside and stare at their screens.
Pokémon Go makes people get off the couch and move.
Initially, screen time was limited to watching TV, then video games and, most recently, smartphones.
It is amazing to see that technology and outdoor exercise do not exclude each other.
Pokémon Go is a game app with characters from a video game created in the 1990s (which was later also made into a series of cartoons, playing cards and other accessories).
Like many popular cultural phenomena, this also paused shortly before the new game became available in the United States, Australia and New Zealand in early July.
The launch in other countries was delayed due to huge interest, which overloaded the servers.
In just a few days, Pokémon Go’s number of users surpassed Tinder and was almost as high as on Twitter.
So how does the game work?
In short, players go out on their smartphones in search of Pokémon, which are tracked by GPS. When a Pokémon is found, it can be "photographed" (via a screenshot of the phone) or "captured".
Wildness has captured the younger generation of video games and lifted their asses off the couch.
In the United States, the game has significantly increased the number of steps a “average person” takes in a day.
The Washington Post recently reported, from the Cardiogram app on the Apple Watch smartwatch, which found within two days of the game’s launch that the number of people moving for 30 minutes a day rose abruptly from 45 percent to 53 percent. The Cardiogram tracks 35,000 users.
The company doesn’t know which users are playing Pokémon Go, it only sees raw data on the amount of exercise.
Many public health campaigns that encourage people to get off the couch and move around for at least 30 minutes a day have fallen on deaf ears because the campaigns have been boring and their advertisers have looked unhappy.
The importance of exercise should not be underestimated.
People who move regularly are less likely to develop cancer or depression.
Exercise helps with weight management, lowers blood pressure, prevents diabetes and brings a large number of other benefits.
The great thing about Pokémon Go is that it makes people do something they enjoy.
In this way, it achieves three basic health benefits – exercise, fresh air and sun and pleasure.
During the hunt, it is possible to make new friends.
As usual, this phenomenon also disapproves of the cheerleaders.
And yes, someone can walk towards the door while playing.
What's the big deal?
The breakthrough is complete.
Because while smartphone apps like Fitbit could have tracked your activity before, they didn’t give you a reason to start, like Pokémon Go does.
The appeal of novelty disappears, and use decreases over time.
However, thanks to the success of Pokémon, there will be more games where apps and virtual reality will be combined with activity in the real world, which will increase the physical activity of people on a yacht and improve their fitness and health.
