In England, about 140,000 people have a heart attack every year, with a quarter of them having a heart attack or having a stroke.
Heart attacks and strokes are caused by the accumulation of fat in the walls of blood vessels, which produces plaques.
If the plaque ruptures, it can cause a blood clot, which prevents blood from entering the heart and causes a heart attack.
And if a blood clot is released, it can travel through the bloodstream and block blood flow to the brain, resulting in a stroke.
The risk of a new attack is higher in people who have had a heart attack once.
Ticagrelor, manufactured by AstraZeneca in the UK and sold under the brand name Brilique, reduces this risk by reducing the likelihood of plugs.
The draft NICE guideline published today recommends that ticagrelor be administered at a dose of 90 mg for the next 12 months, followed by a dose reduction to 60 mg, followed by aspirin twice daily for a further three years.
Carole Longson, a professor at the Center for the Adoption of Treatments (NICE), says: “While effective treatments are available to effectively prevent disease progression and the development of symptoms, up to a quarter of those who have had a heart attack have a new attack or stroke – often with fatal consequences.
Fear of recurrence can have a very negative impact on a person’s quality of life.
