A bit of robbery ahead - criminal intelligence helps in the investigation of crimes and exposes serious crime - ESS.fi
Since the beginning of 2014, each of Finland’s 11 police departments has had a criminal intelligence and analysis unit (RTA).
The operation of the unit is invisible from the outside.
In the Häme Police Department, the unit consists of a total of four police officers in Lahti and Hämeenlinna.
It's drawn by a sergeant stationed in the Bay.
The Chief of Staff is the Inspector in Lahti.
In addition, the strength of the unit includes a civilian dedicated to information technology in Hämeenlinna.
They all work in civilian clothes.
The unit has demonstrated its usefulness and necessity, says Deputy Chief of Police Tero Seppänen.
The RTA unit produces various reports for the rest of the police.
It has, among other things, acquired information on asylum seekers.
The most recent reform of working methods
The establishment of analysis units is the latest reform of police working methods.
The aim has been to prevent crime, i.e. to make it less common for the police to go to the swamps only when they receive an alarm.
With the help of information collected and analysed by the unit, day-to-day police activities are targeted where they are most needed.
With the reform of the police administration, one criminal intelligence centre was established in the country, with less than three national units and a separate criminal intelligence unit for each police department.
The PTR centre, which operates in connection with the Central Crime Police in Vantaa, manages its operations nationwide.
According to their name, PTR units employ people from the Police, Customs and the Border Guard.
RTA units, on the other hand, work in areas divided by police departments and are responsible for providing information to both local police forces and national units.
Inquiry extends beyond your own territory
While an individual police officer is aware of what has happened during his 12-hour shift, it is the task of the RTA unit to know what is happening throughout the police department.
Intelligence also extends beyond the boundaries of one’s own institution, because so does crime.
Those working in the RTA unit have better computer skills than the basic police.
With the help of registers, an alert task database and observations, the unit seeks to draw the attention of the police to new phenomena, productive criminals or similar crimes.
This is called serialization, and it is one of the most important tools for criminal intelligence.
All people have their own way of doing things.
A handprint is also visible at work, whether it is honest or criminal.
Based on the method, a certain image of the author is formed.
Serialization can be done either on the basis of the method of the act or on the basis of the person, depending on which of the police has more information.
Criminals learn from their mistakes
The employees of the RTA unit do not walk around the city with their collars up, but their work is not completely public.
The methods used by both criminals and themselves are not reported, as this could lead to professional criminals developing their activities in order to prevent police efforts to combat crime.
The police will announce the methods publicly if they anticipate that they pose a threat.
Such a case was, for example, the way in which empty dwellings were marked, which was reported in early summer, in apartment burglaries.
In it, the authors put a stick, a pin, or a piece of tape on the front door of the apartment to test whether the residents were really traveling.
The preliminary investigation material shall be made public at least to the parties concerned.
The analysis unit has found that the most professional criminals learn from their mistakes.
The smartest people order the minutes of the district court, which may indicate, for example, that fingerprints have been found at the site.
Next time, the thieves go with their gloves on.
Deputy Police Chief Tero Seppää from the Häme Police Department, Inspector Tuomo Lepola from the Eastern Finland Police Department, Detective Inspector Sami Joutjärve from the Joensuu Police Station and Detective Inspector Arto Tuomela from the Central Criminal Police Department have been interviewed for the case.
The police collect and analyze information that is used to plan practical activities.
Against the background of the decrease in labour and financial volumes.
The first steps towards a new approach were taken 30 years ago.
The most recent change was a three-step reform of PORA, which ended at the end of 2013.
National co-operation gathers information from outside the borders of the institution and Finland.
