The charm of vinyl: who buys records?
Lonely, middle-aged men love vinyl.
Before you can write your angry objection in the comments section under the nickname NotAllLonelyMen of Middle Ages, this statement is based on actual research data.
According to YouGov research company, the much-discussed new arrival of vinyl records is not the result of a millennial-generation boom, when millennials want to feel a physical object in their hands, but instead is the result of middle-aged nostalgia.
A person who recently bought a vinyl album is most likely between the ages of 45 and 54.
In fact, people between the ages of 18 and 24 are the least likely buyers.
It’s also not just the hobbyists’ desire to get records, but the significance is emotional: older vinyl buyers are slightly more likely to hide their emotions (56% vs. 53%) and enjoy being alone (69% vs. 66%).
But are YouGov’s results correct?
If this blog were a TV newscast, the camera would follow me as I walk along the lively Soho Street, wearing a jewelless gray suit. I would lively, bend my hand to a cup and say something traditional, like, "Let's find out."
So let's find out.
While Soho has slowly lost its charm and roughness as hotels, Eats, Prets, and Paperchase chains have taken over former privately owned spaces, there are still a handful of specialty record stores left.
I would probably ask the photographer to stop the camera for a moment as I look very close to the men visiting these shops and try to assess their age and temperament by observing.
Stuart, 55, Glasgow, who I follow from Sister Ray (at the time two young women, three middle-aged men) to Reckless Records (at the time eight middle-aged men, one probably 20-year-old woman) is on a meeting trip in London for the afternoon and spends his extra time exploring the shops.
I'll ask him if he's a collector.
"I think I am," he says.
"I have about 3,000 to 4,000 records."
These boards fill her living room wall, as you can see from the photo. (Stuart sent me the photo by email, I did not follow him home.)
The reason he has acquired such a large number of albums and singles is partly due to his disposable income. He is now able to buy records that he could not afford when they first appeared, and re-buy things that he had had to sell when he was young and broke.
"I get a lot of late '60s and early '70s stuff that popped up when I was 11 or 12 and probably too young to get it," she says.
He agrees that people who buy vinyl records are more likely to be introverts who enjoy their own company, and adds, “I don’t smoke and I don’t drink much.
It's my vice."
Wez, 25, who works at Sister Ray, also believes that many of their customers fit the YouGov profile.
However, he has noticed a new kind of flow of people affected by media hype. These people have heard about the re-entry of vinyl records and now feel compelled to buy back their old records.
"Based on my conversations, people had generally given up their collections around 1998 or 1999.
"Customers who sold their vinyl to buy CDs now sell their CDs to buy their vinyl back," he said.
This may explain the boom in vinyl arousal at a certain age.
What about the alleged emotional significance of the recordings?
In just a few seconds, a movement like Phonica realizes that they provide a comforting community for like-minded people.
According to Wez, some of the older customers have been particularly offended by the contactless payment system.
The digital world may dazzle some vinyl fans, for whom returning to familiar record cases means permanence and reminds them of the happy days of their youth.
"I think it sometimes fills a gap or acquires material possessions for some kind of consolation," says Wez.
"I saw it myself as a collector, and I think so many others.
It’s an easy way to get your mind off.”
"We're like social workers!" whispered Wez's colleague from behind the pile of records.
An ICM poll conducted in April revealed that nearly 50% of those who bought the vinyl album in the previous month had not yet listened to their album.
The poll also found that 41% of people have a turntable that they never use, and 7% of those who buy a vinyl record do not have a turntable at all.
At this point in the newscast, I would probably show a serious face while looking at stacked bossa nova collections.
The re-entry of the vinyl albums is also accompanied by the "pokal phenomenon" observed by Jonny, 42, a salesman for the Sounds of the Universe (currently three middle-aged men).
"A customer recently came to the store and said he doesn't have a turntable, but he wants to buy a Radiohead disc so he can put it on his shelf," Jonny said.
"The proportion of such customers is not high, but they are.
For them, materiality is more important than music.
Some of our customers say they don't have a record player yet.
They’re younger, not older, mostly teenagers who’re just starting a hobby.”
The customer base is much more varied at Foppi, where I'll be arriving next. The shop has dedicated a whole layer to the vinyls.
The guests include seventy-something couples, photo-taking tourists, teenage boys and middle-aged women.
The variety of customers is delighted, even though the atmosphere is not as relaxed as in the previous stores: instead of rocking jazz, the newest sex-filled synthesizer pop from Wild Beasts is from the speakers.
None of the clients seem particularly lonely, but it is difficult to detect a nagging psychological trauma by standing next to someone for 30 seconds.
Elanora, 27, has been walking around Fop for a few minutes and watching various discs on sale.
He's more interested in watching than in shopping.
He says his income is low, so it is not possible for him to collect records.
“They cost a lot.
It’s easy to listen to music from the computer or otherwise, but the fineness of the wine is ...”, he sighs and continues:
"I can't explain it, they're so unique."
My last stop is a store that is said to have inspired a new generation of vinyl fans: Urban Outfitters.
I see a bunch of teenage girls who would imagine jumping in jeans shorts, but instead gather around Polaroid cameras for a while. I see a father and daughter thinking about buying a Crosley disc player.
On the left is a staircase with a wall filled with records from Adele, Jeff Buckley, Amy Winehouse, and Fleetwood Mac: a mix of contemporary music and classics, key records for any average collection.
No one looks at the wall, perhaps because they are just a decorative element and some are so high that you can’t even reach them.
They are pure "art vinyl" interiors.
But considering that any way to get attention to these records might mean more money for the industry and send a few customers on a search trip to Soho, there is little to complain about.
It’s no surprise that the population group most likely to have more time and money than most is also the group that spends the most money on luxuries like vinyl records.
While my research shows that YouGov’s results are true, at least in Soho’s record stores, they don’t rule out a large number of female collectors and vinyl fans that actually exist in both record stores and online forums.
These people are likely to be closely attached to school or working life.
They certainly won’t spend their Thursday mornings snorting at Berwick Street record stores, browsing through records, and avoiding a 30-year-old television host staring at unsuspecting middle-aged men.
