Over the past three years, the price of food has fallen the second most in Finland in those EU countries that have the same wage level as Finland.
In comparison, only in the UK the price of food has fallen faster than in Finland.
The data are based on an article by Statistics Finland’s Development Manager Ilkka Lehtinen, published in the Tieto & Trendit blog.
Lehtinen compared real prices, i.e. prices proportional to the general development of consumer prices.
The latest data are from June of this year.
In the early 2010s, food prices rose sharply.
In 2013, prices fell close to the 1994 price level.
The situation was alarming.
"We were close to losing the price advantage that came with EU membership," Lehtinen says.
Then came a turnaround, after which food has become cheaper every year.
The price is now weighed down by Russia’s bans on food imports, which have stopped food exports from Finland to Russia.
Therefore, the supply of milk and meat products on the Finnish market has increased and agricultural producer prices have decreased.
“Putin’s policy has helped Finnish consumers in the short term,” says Lehtinen.
Intensified price competition between industry and trade has also contributed to the fall in prices.
The large retail chains S Group and Kesko have both lowered their prices.
For consumers, price competition has been seen as a spectacular advertising campaign.
However, Finland is still not a place of cheap food, even though the price of food has fallen considerably.
In 2015, food in Finland was the fourth most expensive of the EU countries, which had a wage level similar to that of Finland.
According to Lehtinen, the price of food sold in Finland is significantly affected by VAT.
He found that if the comparator countries had the same VAT rate, the third cheapest food would be sold in Finland from countries with similar wage levels.
Lehtinen compared Finland to Denmark, Sweden, Austria, France, Italy, the United Kingdom, Germany and the Netherlands.
If the VAT rate were seven, only Germans and Dutch would sell cheaper food than Finns.
"If we want to get to the same level as the old EU countries when it comes to food prices, we need to halve VAT to the EU average and continue to compete on prices," Lehtinen writes.
Mr Lehtinen points out that his calculations of the VAT rate are indicative.
