Congressional Expert Group Says Military Officials Distorted Intelligence on ISIS
A group of Congressional experts released a report Thursday that officials in the U.S. military, the Central Command, altered intelligence reports to give a more optimistic picture of the war against ISIS in Iraq and Syria than what happened on the ground.
The Republican chairs of the House Armed Services Committee, a subcommittee responsible for intelligence and defense budgets, set up a working group to report on the "public discontent" of military intelligence analysts, who said senior military officials were embellishing their assessments of American actions against ISIS.
Central Command, in short Centcom, is the headquarters of the United States Armed Forces in Tampa, Florida, responsible for military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
“The intelligence findings approved by Centcom’s senior executives generally gave a more positive picture of U.S. counter-terrorism activity than the facts on the ground showed, and were invariably more positive than what other intelligence services had analyzed,” the report said in a press release.
“Centcom’s events are unacceptable – our soldiers are suffering when high-level policymakers are presented with false analyses,” California Republican Ken Calvert said in a statement.
“Centcom’s management errors extend to the top level of the organization.”
The 10-page report details the ongoing problems encountered in 2014 and 2015 in Central Command’s descriptions and analyses of American efforts to train Iraqi troops.
While the report does not contain conclusive evidence that reports commissioned by the Obama administration have been falsified, it does give analysts the impression that Centcom executives would have pressured them to present a more optimistic view of the threat posed by ISIS.
"In the first half of 2015, many of Central Command's press releases, statements and testimony to Congress were significantly more positive than what actually happened," the report said.
"For example, a Centcom official made a public statement that a major military offensive to recapture Mosul could take place as early as April or May 2015."
Mosul, the second largest city in Iraq, is still under Islamic State control.
"After months of research, this is very clear," Kansas Republican Mike Pompeo said in a statement.
“From mid-2014 to mid-2015, top-ranked intelligence leaders in the U.S. armed forces manipulated the intelligence obtained to minimize the threat of ISIS in Iraq.”
Republicans set up a task force after they learned of the analysts’ suspicions that intelligence on ISIS had been manipulated.
The report, published on Thursday, will be followed by more detailed results, as the studies continue.
In addition, the Department of Defense’s Chief Inspector has launched an investigation into Centcom’s intelligence.
On Thursday, the Democratic members of the House Intelligence Committee published their own findings, which were in part consistent with the Republican working group’s conclusions.
"Between 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an overly limited process to evaluate intelligence on ISIS and Iraqi security forces," said Adam B. Schiff, a senior Democrat on the committee.
According to Schiff, this process “delayed the publication of intelligence results, violated the morale of analysts” and “insufficiently pays attention to divergent views.”
However, Schiff and the Democrats said there was no evidence that the White House tried to pressure Centcom analysts to adjust its conclusions to a “predetermined or political official line.”
The Daily Beast reported Tuesday on the preliminary results of a congressional study.
Last August, the New York Times reported an investigation by the Pentagon's Chief Inspector, which began as a result of lawsuits filed by Centcom analysts.
Pentagon spokesman, Lt. Commander Patrick Evans, said in a statement that the Department of Defense will not comment on the Congressional report as long as the Inspector General's investigation is ongoing.
However, he says: “Experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and the intelligence community and the Department of Defense welcome a wholesome dialogue on these key national security issues.”
The investigation has other repercussions besides attempting to determine whether the US-led bombings in Iraq and Syria have been successful (accused by an increasing number of defence authorities).
However, the allegations made last year cast doubt on President Obama's ability to rely on the Central Command and its ability to make honest assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis areas.
Criticism of intelligence about IS responds to disagreements that arose more than a decade ago when Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker published a study that found that, despite protests by many analysts, the government of President George W. Bush supported only small troops in Iraq and spent little time pondering the consequences of the 2003 invasion.
Hooker also played a key role in the revolt against intelligence on ISIS.
According to the authorities, last year, the Hooker team came to the conclusion that, despite public statements to the contrary, the air strikes on IS-controlled refineries had not significantly weakened the economy of the terrorist group, as it had built temporary refineries and was thus able to sell oil on the black market.
However, the results of the study were not passed on outside the Central Command, The Times reported in September.
Centcom's then commander, General Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized last year after many legislators had judged the testimony given to the Senate to have been too positive about the war.
General Austin retired in April and was replaced by General Joseph L. Votel as Commander of the Central Command.
