An entire generation protests in Ethiopia, a long-standing ally of the United States
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Government forces have forcibly dispersed protests calling for political change across Ethiopia.
Witnesses say several protesters have been shot dead in clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia falling apart?
For the past decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa and a reliable ally of the West, whose economy has grown rapidly.
In recent months, however, the country has been shaken by anti-government protests that are spreading over ever wider areas.
Last week alone, thousands of people rushed into the streets demanding a fundamental political change.
According to human rights groups, the government’s reaction was ruthless.
Witnesses said police shot and killed several unarmed demonstrators.
The videos of the demonstrations, supposedly at the end of last year or early this year, show how security forces beat young people with sticks who have been forced to stand with their hands against the wall.
The UN chief human rights officer is now calling for an in-depth investigation.
"Holding the country together has always been difficult, and moving forward is all the more difficult," says Rashid Abdi, Research Director of the International Crisis Group of the Horn of Africa project.
Ethiopia is the second-largest country in Africa after Nigeria, with the West contributing to its stability.
The U.S. military and intelligence services are closely supporting the Ethiopians in the fight against terrorist threats throughout the region, particularly in Somalia, and few African countries, if any, receive this much help from the West.
Ethiopia’s economy has grown rapidly.
Its infrastructure has been radically improved, with the capital city of Addis Ababa even having a new urban train.
The streets of cities are usually peaceful, safe and clean.
Ethiopia, however, is still far from being a model country for democracy: human rights organisations have been constantly reporting on the repressive policies of the government, the opposition in the country is very limited and dissidents are quickly silenced.
Many people have been deported, imprisoned, killed or driven far into the wilderness.
But the situation may be changing.
"If the people are repressed and have no choice but to protest, they will erupt," said Seyoum Teshome, a University Lecturer in Central Ethiopia.
“All the young people are demonstrating.
A whole generation of protesters.”
There are many reasons for dissatisfaction, ranging from the use of land to the government coalition’s stranglehold on power.
After the widely criticised elections last year, the ruling party and its allies gained the last seat previously held by the opposition, with the result that they now rule the entire parliament.
At the same time, tensions are growing on the Eritrean border, where the escalating situation claimed hundreds of lives in the battle in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less defeated in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden People’s Liberation Front, may seek to exploit the turmoil and re-arm themselves.
There are many reasons why a bitter mood that has been smearing beneath the surface for years now erupts.
The first is obviously innocent: smartphones.
Only in the last couple of years have Ethiopians been able to communicate on social media as cheaper smartphones became commonplace and internet access improved.
Even though the government repeatedly blocks access to Facebook and Twitter, especially during protests, many still access the internet through mediation servers that conceal their whereabouts.
Many Ethiopian youths reported that this is how they invited people to demonstrations.
Another reason is the increase in solidarity between the two largest population groups in Ethiopia, the Oromo and the Amharic.
The Oromo and the Amharic are not natural allies.
Amharic people, mostly from the Christian highlands of Ethiopia, have long dominated the country's politics and business and exploited the oroms, many of which are Muslim and live in the lowlands.
But this is also changing.
"The cooperation is deepening and we are getting under the same umbrella," says Mulatu Gemechu, oromo director.
The biggest protests have been in the Oromo and Amharic regions.
Many Amharic and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unjustly ruled by the tigre tribe, which represents only about six percent of the population, but still dominates the army, intelligence, trade, and politics.
The third cause of the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Former rebel leader Meles was Prime Minister of Ethiopia for 17 years until he died of an unnamed illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius who could see around the corner.
Analysts said he was particularly skilled at detecting the first signs of dissatisfaction and using ambassadors to mediate between opponents.
"The current government lacks this essential instinct," says conflict researcher Abdi.
Ethiopia’s new Prime Minister Hailemariam Desalegn stepped into the shoes of Meles.
Unlike Meles, who was from the Tigre region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say he doesn’t have the trust of security forces run by the Tiger tribe.
Many fear that this will mean more bloodshed.
The last time such riots took place in Ethiopia was in 2005, when thousands protested against elections that the government, according to analysts, first screwed up and then stole.
In the aftermath of the protests, many protesters were killed, although the death toll was lower than in the previous months, and the unrest ceased relatively quickly.
Development experts have praised Ethiopian leaders for their far-sighted infrastructure planning, such as the new urban train, and for significant progress in the fight against poverty.
But the internal resentment against the Ethiopian government has clearly not prevented the intensification.
And resentment is taking on a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month in Gondar, Amharic city, protesters attacked companies owned by tigers, and hate speech against tigers is on the rise on social media.
Analysts say the protests put the United States and other Western allies in a difficult position.
The U.S. government has used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned aircraft monitoring neighboring Somalia, but the base has recently been closed, the U.S. says.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, it also does not want its allies in an already unstable region to collapse.
"This requires a strict balance," says Abdi.
