The Cruel Food of the Great Depression in a New Work: A Square Meal
In March 1933, shortly after becoming president, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat down for lunch in his office in the White House.
Known as a culinary artist, President Roosevelt was fond of the luxurious cuisine of Fifth Avenue restaurants, such as foie gras and Maryland turtle soup.
On that day, his menu was more modest: deviled eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes and plum pudding for dessert.
"It was a demonstration of culinary solidarity with the people who are suffering," says Jane Ziegelman.
Her husband, Andrew Coe, adds: “It was also a message to Americans how they should eat.”
The couple living in Brooklyn Heights both work as food historians.
Coe’s latest book, Chop Suey, tells the story of Chinese cuisine in America, while Ziegelman’s latest book, 97 Orchard, tells the story of an apartment building on the Lower East Side through food.
Their new co-production is the A Square Meal, published by Harper and published on Tuesday, depicting the history of American food during the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The couple showed their own culinary solidarity by agreeing to meet with the journalist at Eisenberg's Sandwich Shop, a small and ordinary lunch bar near the Flatiron skyscraper and opened in the same year as the big stock market crash in 1929.
Ziegelman, 54, ordered a sandwich filled with cream cheese and olives, while Coe, 57, ordered turkey, mashed potatoes and mixed vegetables.
When the reporter ordered the meatloaf, the couple said it would be suitable for a discussion about eating during a very large recession.
"The worries were very popular," says Jane Ziegelman.
"People ate peanut crumbs, liver crumbs and bean crumbs.
They were made of materials that were cheap and sufficient.
Imagine eating enough peanuts to eat the whole meal.”
Andrew Coe is grinning.
"It must have pressed like lead in the stomach," he says.
Before the Great Depression, the American dining table, especially in the countryside, operated on the buffet principle of "eating as much as you want".
Women cooked food for farm workers, and freshly fried pies were served for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
It was the Americans who had sent food to starving Europeans during World War I. A Square Meal is a chronicle of how the people survived when abundance suddenly had to be abandoned.
“This was a time when food became a central and distressing topic for Americans,” says Coe, explaining why he and his wife wanted to write about it.
Equally distressing was the new low-cost diet: according to Ziegelman, enigmatic dishes such as marshmallows and stews became the main food, and stews were described as "a great way to exploit food leftovers" because chefs could cover up unattractive ingredients with cream sauce.
Fresh fruits were replaced by cheaper dried fruits.
Meat, which for years had been the central part of the American meal, became a sparingly used luxury.
We experimented with strange mixtures, where the most important thing was the fulfillment of calorie and nutritional values rather than taste or even common sense in the kitchen.
While conducting research for a book that also includes recipes, Jane Ziegelman prepared peanut-butter-filled onions as a scarcity-time dish.
"It did not gain popularity at the dinner table," says Coe,
Ziegelman adds: “It was unreal.
Peanut butter and onion do not go together at all.
This was characteristic of many household recipes.”
Household experts, such as Louise Stanley, who served as the director of the Federal Household Office from 1923 to 1943, guided citizens’ eating habits in an unprecedented and unique way.
They published recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines and encouraged women to be precise budgeters and to meet the challenge of making crispy dishes like carrots and cream-pagates tasty.
A Square Meal is a celebration of historical treats.
Particularly tasty are reports of the government's reactions to its hungry citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover's 'let me eat cake' attitude.
While publicly praising the simple food of his childhood on an Iowa farm, he himself ate like the millionaire and sophisticated gentleman he had become.
"He liked continental European cuisine like fish and cucumber sauce," says Coe.
"He ate in a nearly gold-plated dining room, wearing a tuxedo.
He was completely alienated from reality.”
President Roosevelt might have made the same mistake if his wife, Eleanor, had not encouraged him to set an example on his belly.
As reported in the book, when Mrs. Roosevelt hired a housekeeper who was not at all interested in taste, the food served in the White House was not only the most boring in Washington, but also the worst prepared.”
Many of the food of the recession was abandoned as soon as the earth got back on its feet.
According to Jane Ziegelman, the continuation of the tradition is still reflected in how we pay attention to calories and dietary intake, and how science has been applied to cooking.
As the couple writes the book, they say they begin to understand more about Ziegelman’s mother’s eating habits, including why she couldn’t throw away food.
"He was really afraid of having to throw away food," says Coe.
"People even started getting sick of his food," Ziegelman recalls.
"For example, once on wind hats."
After the main plates were emptied at Eisenberg's lunch bar, Ziegelman and Coe picked up the plum dessert they had made at home, the same one President Roosevelt ate at lunch.
"It's called plum foam," says Ziegelman and adds that giving a spectacular name to modest recipes was a common trick.
There was no whipped cream, just plums, a little flour, sugar, water and cinnamon.
We reluctantly immersed our spoons in thick brown lumps.
Surprisingly, it didn’t taste bad.
Coe sacked a second and a third time.
"German nuts would make this better," Coe says to his wife, sounding like a positive budgeter.
