Kepler measures the rotational speed of stars in the Pleiadian cluster
The most recent mission of the Kepler Space Telescope has been to measure the speed of stellar rotation, which has helped astronomers compile the most comprehensive list of the speeds of stars in the Pleiadian star cluster to date.
Based on new data, astronomers will be able to find out why stars in the same star cluster rotate at different speeds and how rotational times are related to the planetary formation.
"We hope that by comparing the results with other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between star weight and age and even the history of its solar system," said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the University of Caltech in Pasadena.
The Pleiadian star cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the star cluster were born about 125 million years ago, which means that they are about to reach adulthood.
They are now spinning faster than ever.
When the rotation speed is at its peak, large amounts of star wind erupt from the stars that are growing up.
These winds have a braking effect on the stars as they travel through the magnetic fields of the stars.
As the star ages, its rotation speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of each star by tracking the time between the appearance of recognisable star spots (corresponding to sunspots).
The latest recorded rotational speed data suggests that larger stars rotate more slowly than smaller ones.
Rebull compares stars to dancers – bigger ones spin slower than smaller ones.
“We see from the Pleiadian ‘dance’ that slow-moving ones are typically larger, while the fastest-moving ones are typically very light stars,” says Rebull.
Because the Pleiadian star cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory to compare the properties of stars in relation to their rotational speeds.
"The Pleiadian star cluster provides a pillar for theoretical models of rotation of both younger and older stars," says Rebull.
We want to learn more about how, when and why stars slow down their rotational speeds and end their "dance."
Rebull and colleagues present their latest analysis of the Pleiadian rotational speeds in three new articles to be published shortly in the Astronomical Journal.
